<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Qwerty12</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I have the latest from the CVS, and from time to time, SEQ will crash on me doing the Seg fault error. Doesn't happen all the time, and it's random. When I'm grouped, when I'm solo, when I'm just standing there, when I loot, when I kill, etc etc. I can't seem to find what is causing it. The message in the terminal window doesn't say anything sides seg fault.<P>Anyone else getting this? RedHat 6.1, normal install (backup kernal though as I'm trying to get SMP workin =), and it's always worked before without a hitch.<P>-Qwerty</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Inocare</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Actually yes I am having the same problem Querty.  I heard that it may be because I was running Gnome/Enlightenment so I switched over to KDE and the problem still occurs and shows the exact same symptoms.<BR>It appears to be working perfectly for some time then for no discernable reason it will Seg Fault on me.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Qwerty12</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Something else that's wierd, is it will stay up and working fine for different amounts of time. Sometinmes it'll crash on zoning, sometimes it'll stay up for 1-5 minutes, sometimes several hours at a time. Many zones are completely fine, some are crash prone (spent some time earlier in Rathe Mountains, it crashed alot - most other zones seemed ok).<P></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Decaying Skeleton</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Just a warning to the development team: It's clear from my crashes (unreported) and others, that there are ways data coming from Verant can crash ShowEQ. The probability is these crashes are caused by buffer overflows, which may be related to trusting the packet data to fit "expected" guidelines, and therefore not doing proper checking.<P>Because may people use ShowEQ as root on their box, and because it's been shown time and again that a buffer overflow can allow arbitrary code to be run as the executing user, as long as ShowEQ is crashable, we are at risk.<P>For people concerned about this risk, you CAN protect yourself and continue to use ShowEQ without modifying the program -- IF you do not need promiscuous mode to access the data. Run ShowEQ as a special user that has no rights to do anything else on your machine.<P>To allow ShowEQ to be safe via code, open the raw socket, place it in promiscuous mode if requested, and drop all root privilages. Prior to dropping root, consider a chdir() to a benign location so no system commands can be executed.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Bellhead</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">No so fast sparky - nothing Verant is doing is craching SEQ - whats causing the SEG faults is a lot of poorly implmented changes by an over enthusiastic coder -checking them in before he really tests them hard - and those changes have broken a lot of other htings, like regex processing in the filter files.<P><BR>Thats why this version took so long - there were and are bugs all over the place.<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sacrificial</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Yeah, what Bellhead said... <P>for anyone interested, a temporary solution to the SEG faulting that seems to work for me is commenting out lines 530 and 531 in showeq/src/map.cpp<P>The lines look like<P>      if (spawnItem[n])<BR>        delete spawnItem[n];<P>and should be changed to<P>//    if (spawnItem[n])<BR>//      delete spawnItem[n];<P>This introduces other problems, such as spawns not being removed from the list after they're gone from the map... but at least it's not SEGfaulting.<P></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Diesel</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Nice fix, it works like a charm now....no dumping and I havent seen any left over spawns like mentioned. But, still playing.<BR>Great Job ShowEQ team!!!!!<P>Thanks<P>Diesel</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Decaying Skeleton</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">My appologies for thinking it was caused by the contents of the data stream. My belief here was fostered by the fact that my initial observations were accompanied by the display of incorrectly decrypted name data. This was coupled with my having better experiences with the performance of ShowEQ previously.<P>Regards,<BR>A pretty happy ShowEQ user.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Qwerty12</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kick ass, hope this works, wish I woulda checked the boards yesterday.<P>I was betting my money on that it was one of two things: Pets or Drops. I tried to filter out drops (added *drop* to the filter), but it didn't work. Heh... I figured it was worth a shot, since *oracle* frickin gets everyone now that has an ORobe on. that was annoying. I haven't had time to go through the code since like 1.6, so Kudos to ya'll who are making changes! <P>The resizing and all the options are awesome.<P>Oh, is zoom in and out using keyboard working? I had a friend over on day, and saw him zooming using keyboard, but I can't figure the damn thing out... *laugh*<P>Thanks!<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">MindWarp</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">use the + and - keys on the numeric keypad (others may work, but I dont use them).<P>Something I was wondering with these seg faults. What happens if you have a npc that has a pet? If you kill the master, the pet doesnt follow the normal rules of suiciding, could this be the problem (no clue, and no time to check)?<P><P>------------------<BR>-_=_MindWarp_=_-<BR>  --========--</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">eq_girl</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I tried to edit the map.ccp as per Sacrificial's post, however, I still get segfaults.  Do I need to run bash or make again?<P>eq_girl</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Qwerty12</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Yeah, yhou have to run the whole thing again, to be safe. You might be able to get by with a recompile and install, not sure. I just do thje whole thing over again, takes 5 minutes.<P>bash autogen.sh<BR>make install<P></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
